======================================================================
PART 1: E₇ EXPONENTS — THE NON-COPRIME ANOMALY
======================================================================

  Exponent analysis — coprime vs non-coprime to h:

  G₂ (h=6): exponents = [1, 5]
    coprime to h: [1, 5] (2 = φ(6)=2? YES)

  F₄ (h=12): exponents = [1, 5, 7, 11]
    coprime to h: [1, 5, 7, 11] (4 = φ(12)=4? YES)

  E₆ (h=12): exponents = [1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11]
    coprime to h: [1, 5, 7, 11] (4 = φ(12)=4? YES)
    NON-coprime to h: [4, 8]
      gcd(4,12) = 4
      gcd(8,12) = 4

  E₇ (h=18): exponents = [1, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17]
    coprime to h: [1, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17] (6 = φ(18)=6? YES)
    NON-coprime to h: [9]
      gcd(9,18) = 9

  E₈ (h=30): exponents = [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
    coprime to h: [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29] (8 = φ(30)=8? YES)

  KEY FINDING: E₆ has non-coprime exponents {4, 8} (gcd with 12 = 4)
  E₇ has non-coprime exponent {9} (gcd(9,18) = 9)
  E₈ has ALL exponents coprime to h=30 (totatives of 30)

  The CS boundary 9 appears as the UNIQUE non-coprime exponent of E₇!
  In E₆, the non-coprime exponents {4,8} have gcd 4 with h=12.
  4 = vertices of tetrahedron = KEY₁².

  Divisors of h for each exceptional:
  G₂ (h=6): divisors = [1, 2, 3, 6]

  F₄ (h=12): divisors = [1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12]

  E₆ (h=12): divisors = [1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12]
    Divisors that are also exponents: [4]

  E₇ (h=18): divisors = [1, 2, 3, 6, 9, 18]
    Divisors that are also exponents: [9]

  E₈ (h=30): divisors = [1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 10, 15, 30]

  For A_n: h=n+1, exponents=1,...,n
  ALL non-trivial divisors of h are exponents!
    A_1 (h=2): divisor-exponents = []
    A_2 (h=3): divisor-exponents = []
    A_3 (h=4): divisor-exponents = [2]
    A_4 (h=5): divisor-exponents = []
    A_5 (h=6): divisor-exponents = [2, 3]
    A_7 (h=8): divisor-exponents = [2, 4]

======================================================================
PART 2: THE 18-GON AND CIRCULANT TOURNAMENTS
======================================================================

  Z₁₈ ≅ Z₂ × Z₉
  Generators: {1, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17} (= units of Z₁₈)
  These are the E₇ COPRIME exponents!

  Units of Z₁₈: [1, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17]
  Number of units: 6 = φ(18) = 6

  Tournament circulants require ODD n:
  18 is even → no circulant tournament on Z₁₈
  But 17 is prime, 17 ≡ 1 (mod 4) → QR_17 is a graph, not tournament
  19 is prime, 19 ≡ 3 (mod 4) → QR_19 IS a tournament!
  19 = 18 + 1 = h(E₇) + 1 ← interesting!

  Paley tournament primes (p ≡ 3 mod 4): [3, 7, 11, 19, 23, 31, 43, 47]

  QR_3  ← KEY₂, C₃
  QR_7  ← 2³-1, Mersenne, Lucas(4)
  QR_11  ← Lucas(5), first SC tournament at n≡3(4)
  QR_19  ← h(E₇)+1=18+1
  QR_23  ← E₈ exponent
  QR_31  ← 2⁵-1, Mersenne
  QR_43  ← E₈ dim component: 248=8·31

======================================================================
PART 3: E₇ WEYL GROUP AND TOURNAMENT STRUCTURE
======================================================================

  |W(E₇)| = 2903040 = 2^10 · 3^4 · 5 · 7
         = 1024 · 81 · 5 · 7

  |S₈| = 8! = 40320 = Weyl group of A₇
  |W(E₇)| / |S₈| = 72.00
  = 72 = 72 = 8 · 9 = rank(E₈) · CS-boundary!

  |W(E₇)| / |W(A₇)| = 72
  72 = 8 · 9 = 2³ · 3² = KEY₁³ · KEY₂²
  This is the product of rank(E₈) and the CS boundary!

  |W(E₈)| = 696729600 = 2^14 · 3^5 · 5^2 · 7
  |W(E₈)| / |S₈| = 17280
  = 17280 (should check)
  17280 = 2^7·3^3·5^1

  |W(E₆)| = 51840
  |W(E₆)| / |S₆| = 72 (S₆ = A₅ Weyl)
  = 72
  = 72 = 8·9 = KEY₁³·KEY₂² AGAIN!

  REMARKABLE: |W(E₆)|/|S₆| = |W(E₇)|/|S₈| = 72 = 8·9!

======================================================================
PART 4: THE EXCEPTIONAL CASCADE
======================================================================

  The exceptional cascade:
  Group   rank  dim    h    det   dim/rank   pos.roots
  G₂     2      14    6    1        7.0      6
  F₄     4      52   12    1       13.0      24
  E₆     6      78   12    3       13.0      36
  E₇     7     133   18    2       19.0      63
  E₈     8     248   30    1       31.0      120

  Dimension ratios (consecutive):
  F₄/G₂ = 3.7143 ≈ 3.7143
  E₆/F₄ = 1.5000 = 3/2 = KEY₂/KEY₁
  E₇/E₆ = 1.7051
  E₈/E₇ = 1.8647

  E₆/F₄ = 78/52 = 3/2 EXACTLY! The ratio of the keys!
  Check: 78 = 52 · 3/2 = 52 · 1.5 = 78 ✓

======================================================================
PART 5: DUAL COXETER NUMBERS
======================================================================

  Dual Coxeter numbers h∨:
    A_n: h∨ = n+1 (same as h)
    B_n: h∨ = 2n-1
    C_n: h∨ = n+1
    D_n: h∨ = 2n-2 (same as h)
    G₂: h∨ = 4 (h=6)
    F₄: h∨ = 9 (h=12)
    E₆: h∨ = 12 (h=12, same)
    E₇: h∨ = 18 (h=18, same)
    E₈: h∨ = 30 (h=30, same)

  For the ADE types (simply-laced): h∨ = h always.
  For non-simply-laced:
    G₂: h∨ = 4 ≠ h = 6. Ratio h/h∨ = 6/4 = 3/2 = KEY₂/KEY₁!
    F₄: h∨ = 9 ≠ h = 12. Ratio h/h∨ = 12/9 = 4/3 = KEY₁²/KEY₂!

  EXTRAORDINARY: h∨(F₄) = 9 = CS BOUNDARY!
  The dual Coxeter number of F₄ is our CS boundary!
  And h(F₄)/h∨(F₄) = 12/9 = 4/3 = KEY₁²/KEY₂

  h∨(G₂) = 4 = KEY₁²
  h∨(F₄) = 9 = KEY₂²
  Pattern: h∨ for non-simply-laced = square of a key!

======================================================================
PART 6: THE 56-DIMENSIONAL REPRESENTATION OF E₇
======================================================================

  E₇ fundamental representations:
  The minuscule representation has dimension 56

  56 = 8 · 7 = C(8,2) - C(8,1) = 28 - 8 + ... no
  56 = C(8,3) = number of 3-element subsets of {1,...,8}

  COINCIDENCE: non-isomorphic tournaments on 6 vertices = 56!
  And dim(minuscule rep of E₇) = 56!

  At n=8 (= rank(E₈)):
  C(8,3) = 56 = 56 = number of 3-element subsets
  Each 3-element subset gives either a 3-cycle or a transitive triple
  In a random tournament, expected 3-cycles = 56/4 = 14

  56 = 2³ · 7 = KEY₁³ · (KEY₁³-1) = KEY₁³ · Mersenne(3)
  This is rank(E₈) · (rank(E₈)-1)

  Adjoint representation: dim = 133 = 7 · 19
  7 = rank(E₇), 19 = h(E₇)+1 = Paley prime!
  133 = rank(E₇) · (h(E₇)+1)

  dim(E₇) = rank · (2h-1+... wait)
  Actually: dim = rank + 2·#pos.roots = 7 + 2·63 = 133
  And #pos.roots = sum of exponents = 63 = 7·9
  63 = rank(E₇) · CS_boundary = 7 · 9!

  E₇ ENCODES THE CS BOUNDARY:
  #positive roots / rank = 63/7 = 9 = CS boundary
  This ratio is the AVERAGE EXPONENT!
  Average exponent of E₇ = 9 = 3² = KEY₂²

======================================================================
PART 7: EXPONENT SUMS AND THE KEYS
======================================================================

  Average exponent (= #pos.roots / rank) for exceptionals:
  G₂: avg = 6/2 = 3.0000 = 3 = KEY₂
  F₄: avg = 24/4 = 6.0000 = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  E₆: avg = 36/6 = 6.0000 = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  E₇: avg = 63/7 = 9.0000 = 9 = KEY₂² = CS boundary
  E₈: avg = 120/8 = 15.0000 = 15 = 3·5 = KEY₂·5

  G₂: avg exponent = 3 = KEY₂
  F₄: avg exponent = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  E₆: avg exponent = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  E₇: avg exponent = 9 = KEY₂² = CS BOUNDARY
  E₈: avg exponent = 15 = 3·5

  The average exponent sequence for exceptionals: 3, 6, 6, 9, 15
  Differences: 3, 0, 3, 6
  Ratios: 2, 1, 3/2, 5/3

  For A_n: avg exponent = (1+2+...+n)/n = (n+1)/2 = h/2
  So avg_exp = h/2 always for type A

  Check: avg_exp = h/2 for ALL simple Lie algebras!
  This is because the exponents m_i satisfy m_i + m_{rank+1-i} = h
  (they come in palindromic pairs summing to h)

  So the CS boundary 9 = h(E₇)/2 = avg exponent of E₇
  is a FUNDAMENTAL invariant of the E₇ Lie algebra.

======================================================================
PART 8: E₇ AS MIDPOINT OF THE EXCEPTIONAL HIERARCHY
======================================================================

  The 5 exceptional Lie groups form a HIERARCHY:

  G₂ ← F₄ ← E₆ ← E₇ ← E₈
  ↓      ↓      ↓      ↓      ↓
  h=6    h=12   h=12   h=18   h=30
  det=1  det=1  det=3  det=2  det=1
  avg=3  avg=6  avg=6  avg=9  avg=15

  E₇ is the 4th of 5 exceptionals by rank (2,4,6,7,8)
  It is the UNIQUE exceptional with:
  - det = 2 = KEY₁ (binary orientation)
  - h/2 = 9 = KEY₂² (CS boundary)
  - h/det = 9 (also the CS boundary)
  - 9 as an exponent (appears in the root system)

  THE KEY ENCODING IN EXCEPTIONAL GROUPS:

  E₆ encodes KEY₂ = 3 through its center Z₃
  E₇ encodes KEY₁ = 2 through its center Z₂
  Together they encode the tournament polynomial z²-5z+6

  E₈ unifies them: det=1 (trivial center),
  but h = 30 = 2·3·5 contains BOTH keys and their sum

  THE DEEPEST CONNECTION:

  In tournament theory: z² - 5z + 6 = (z-2)(z-3) = 0
  In Lie theory: A₁ and A₂ have Cartan eigenvalues {2} and {1,3}
  The tournament polynomial roots ARE Cartan eigenvalues!

  More precisely:
  KEY₁ = 2 = max eigenvalue of Cartan(A₁) = det(A₁) = h(A₁)
  KEY₂ = 3 = max eigenvalue of Cartan(A₂) = det(A₂) = h(A₂)

  And their difference pattern reappears in the exceptionals:
  det(E₆) = KEY₂ = 3
  det(E₇) = KEY₁ = 2
  h(E₇)/det(E₇) = 9 = KEY₂² = CS boundary
  h∨(F₄) = 9 = CS boundary (dual Coxeter of F₄)

  THE TOURNAMENT UNIVERSE IS THE A₁-A₂ UNIVERSE,
  REFLECTED IN THE EXCEPTIONAL GROUPS E₆ AND E₇.

======================================================================
PART 9: NUMERICAL COINCIDENCES AS STRUCTURAL ECHOES
======================================================================

  Verified coincidences:
  56 = dim(minuscule E₇) = T(6) (non-iso tournaments on 6)
  56 = C(8,3) = potential 3-cycles on 8 vertices

  72 = |W(E₆)|/6! = 72
  72 = |W(E₇)|/8! = 72
  72 = 8·9 = rank(E₈)·CS_boundary = KEY₁³·KEY₂²

  63 = #pos.roots(E₇) = 7·9 = rank·CS_boundary
  63 = 2^6-1 = Mersenne(6)

  120 = #pos.roots(E₈) = 5! = |BI| (binary icosahedral)
  120 = C(10,3) = ... or 2³·3·5 = KEY₁³·KEY₂·5

  Evaluating tournament polynomial z²-5z+6 at various points:
  f(0) = 6  ← |val|=6 is a Coxeter number
  f(1) = 2
  f(2) = 0  ← ROOT (z=2)
  f(3) = 0  ← ROOT (z=3)
  f(4) = 2
  f(5) = 6  ← |val|=6 is a Coxeter number
  f(6) = 12  ← Coxeter number!, |val|=12 is a Coxeter number
  f(7) = 20

  f(0) = 6 = h(G₂)!
  f(1) = 2 = KEY₁ = det(E₇)!
  f(4) = -2 = -KEY₁
  f(5) = 6 = h(G₂) again! (by symmetry: f(5-x)=f(x) since 5=sum of roots)

  The tournament polynomial has AXIS OF SYMMETRY at z = 5/2!
  f(5/2 + t) = f(5/2 - t) for all t
  The symmetric point 5/2 = (KEY₁+KEY₂)/2

  f at Cartan eigenvalues of A₂: {1, 3}
  f(1) = 2 = 2 = KEY₁
  f(3) = 0 = 0 (root!)

  So f(smaller eigenvalue of A₂) = KEY₁ = larger eigenvalue of A₁!
  This creates a SELF-REFERENTIAL LOOP:
  A₂'s eigenvalues → through tournament poly → back to A₁'s eigenvalue
